posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>127692438
>I notice that in soccer, offensive players tend to receive almost all of the praise. Is this just grug-brain thinking that more goals=better player, or are attackers legitimately more valuable

Football used to be way more offensive.
As it grew more defensive, defenders also became more valuable.
However, it's still true that the most talented players become forwards/midfielders. Usually in youth academy everyone wants to be the forward, so only the best manage to stay in that position, while the others are 'relegated' to being defenders, keepers, etc.

Also, a goal is the most important moment in football, it's the highlight of every match. It's not uncommon for a whole team to be playing pretty badly, until a forward has a stroke of genius and scores a goal out of nothing, putting his team in front against all odds.
I just googled some Ice Hockey scores and it seems to be at the range five or six goals per game, all in sixty minutes. In football, most of the games end in 1-1, 2-1, 1-0, 0-0, a 3-2 game is already a game full of goals (even if it lasts 120+ minutes, like the WC final). This is part of the excitement of the game, and what keeps us glued to the screen - if we go away for one minute, maybe we'll miss the game-changing goal (alas, this happens all too often).
Hence it's no wonder that the goal-scores gets a lot more attention, for it's him who has the real potential to completely change the game *for the good*, while a defender who changes the course of the game is almost always doing it *for the bad* of the team.

Despite all that, some of the very greatest and most famous players are defenders. The single most famous Italian and German players, for instance, were both defenders (Beckenbauer and Maldini), and the most famous Russian was a keeper (Yashin).

If we didn't have Messi and Ronaldo playing at such a crazy level in the last decade, Emmanuel Neuer, Xavi, Iniesta, and other non-forwards would have won the Ballon d'Or.
